%I A395371 #17 May 13 2026 16:04:49
%S A395371 1,1,4,36,641,19948,851390,47252043,3190674132
%N A395371 a(n) is the number of triples (A->B, B->C, C->A) of pairwise disjoint paths on a triangular grid ABC of side length n, such that the distance from the starting point to each point of a path is always increasing.
%C A395371 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles with x-axis defined along AB and y-axis defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), B has coordinates (n,0) and C is (0,n).
%C A395371 A grid point (x,y) on a path of a point P moving from A to B satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path.
%C A395371 x + y <= n, y <= n/2 and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point.
%C A395371 Symmetry can be used to transform any path from A to B into a corresponding path from B to C or a path C to A. In particular, if (h,k) is a point on a path from A to B, then (n-h-k,h) and (k,n-h-k) are the corresponding points on a path from B to C or a path from C to A, respectively.
%C A395371 Paths are disjoint if they do not share any common point other than their starting or finishing corners.
%C A395371 Paths do not need to have equal length.
%e A395371 n = 2 has only one triplet of disjoint paths:
%e A395371 Grid paths from A to B:
%e A395371  P1: {(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395371  P2: {(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A395371  P3: {(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)}.
%e A395371 Grid paths from B to C:
%e A395371  S1: {(2,0), (1,0), (0,1), (0,2)},
%e A395371  S2: {(2,0), (1,1), (0,1), (0,2)},
%e A395371  S3: {(2,0), (1,1), (0,2)}.
%e A395371 Grid paths from C to A:
%e A395371  R1: {(0,2), (1,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A395371  R2: {(0,2), (0,1), (1,0), (0,0)},
%e A395371  R3: {(0,2), (0,1), (0,0).
%e A395371 The only valid set is: {(P3,S3,R3)}, therefore a(2) = 1.
%Y A395371 Cf. A394698, A393490, A395036.
